Suppose $x_{1}, x_{2}$, and $x_{3}$ are random samples from three independent normal distributions.
Random samples with the required correlation structure are $\varepsilon_{1}, \varepsilon_{2}, \varepsilon_{3}$ where

$$
\begin{gathered}
\varepsilon_{1}=x_{1} \\
\varepsilon_{2}=\rho_{12} x_{1}+x_{2} \sqrt{1-\rho_{12}^{2}}
\end{gathered}
$$

and

$$
\varepsilon_{3}=\alpha_{1} x_{1}+\alpha_{2} x_{2}+\alpha_{3} x_{3}
$$

where

$$
\begin{gathered}
\alpha_{1}=\rho_{13} \\
\alpha_{1} \rho_{12}+\alpha_{2} \sqrt{1-\rho_{12}^{2}}=\rho_{23}
\end{gathered}
$$

and

$$
\alpha_{1}^{2}+\alpha_{2}^{2}+\alpha_{3}^{2}=1
$$

This means that

$$
\begin{gathered}
\alpha_{1}=\rho_{13} \\
\alpha_{2}=\frac{\rho_{23}-\rho_{12} \rho_{12}}{\sqrt{1-\rho_{12}^{2}}} \\
\alpha_{3}=\sqrt{1-\alpha_{1}^{2}-\alpha_{2}^{2}}
\end{gathered}
$$
